The paper proposes a novel framework for landmark localization in non-rigid objects using convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and geometric constraints. This makes it highly likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves training deep neural networks, which suggests it could also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also mentions benchmarks for facial landmark localization, human body pose estimation, and bird part localization, indicating that it could belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the use of thin-plate spline transformations, which suggests it could also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
